00:12:00.940 --> 00:12:08.599
One other question was, how performant or fast is Tidy Models compared to other frameworks

00:12:08.599 --> 00:12:11.080
in R?

00:12:11.080 --> 00:12:20.479
So Tidy Models doesn't implement the algorithms used to train the models ourselves.

00:12:20.479 --> 00:12:24.640
We make use of existing packages in R to make that happen.

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:29.679
And then we have a layer on top that sort of standardizes the way that you interface

00:12:29.679 --> 00:12:32.239
with those models.

00:12:32.239 --> 00:12:37.880
Earlier this year, we spent a good amount of time making sure that the layer on top

00:12:37.960 --> 00:12:43.159
of those existing R packages that we've written is as performant as possible.

00:12:43.159 --> 00:12:50.580
So once you're training more complex models or you're working with data that most people

00:12:50.580 --> 00:12:55.440
will see in an applied context, that overhead is basically negligible.

00:12:55.440 --> 00:13:01.960
So your modeling pipeline is as fast as is otherwise possible in R.

00:13:02.039 --> 00:13:09.559
We also have a few tricks up our sleeves to reduce the amount of models that you actually

00:13:09.559 --> 00:13:14.880
need to train to still be able to evaluate many models at once.

00:13:14.880 --> 00:13:25.840
And we try to make it very easy to accidentally do the most performant approach to a modeling

00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:30.119
problem that somebody might be tackling.

