And so that would be our recommendation, mostly because that's what Vetiver kind of

00:19:16.959 --> 00:19:21.319
suggests. It gives you the tools to actually easily create that the API.

00:19:21.359 --> 00:19:24.959
So and even if you've never created an API before, check it out.

00:19:24.959 --> 00:19:31.000
I go to the Vetiver GitHub pages and they have some examples on how to create a very

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:32.160
simple API.

00:19:32.560 --> 00:19:38.280
Because if you're like me, when I started kind of dipping my toes into the API world, I

00:19:38.280 --> 00:19:41.359
thought I was going to be way in over my head because it's like APIs, that's super

00:19:41.359 --> 00:19:42.920
scary. But it's not.

00:19:43.719 --> 00:19:45.319
Vetiver makes it insanely easy.

00:19:45.319 --> 00:19:49.119
And then you can take that API, you can host it on Connect, and it will continue to run

00:19:49.119 --> 00:19:50.160
there forever.

00:19:50.160 --> 00:19:51.920
So it's always ready to be interacted with.

00:19:54.119 --> 00:19:55.160
Yeah, that's a great answer.

00:19:56.959 --> 00:20:04.520
Awesome. I really liked your explanation of an API, Ryan, in one of the workflow demos

00:20:04.520 --> 00:20:07.880
that you gave, and there's a blog post that goes along with it, so I'm going to share

00:20:07.880 --> 00:20:10.040
that in the chat here, too.

00:20:12.280 --> 00:20:19.560
But another question that came over on Slido was, how could I use tidy models to retrain

00:20:19.560 --> 00:20:23.040
a model after getting new data in order to update it?

00:20:27.040 --> 00:20:33.680
So part of this question, I think, comes back to the CICD.

00:20:34.640 --> 00:20:43.119
I think, so if you're getting new data on a continuous basis and you want to run the

00:20:43.119 --> 00:20:49.599
whole modeling pipeline all the way through, then you can use the same script that you

00:20:49.599 --> 00:20:55.680
used to fit the model in the first place and connect it through continuous integration

00:20:55.680 --> 00:20:58.079
in the same way like we discussed before.

00:20:58.400 --> 00:21:03.199
But I think another part of the question is like, is there a way to interface with the

00:21:03.920 --> 00:21:07.839
model updating methods that some modeling engines have and are?

00:21:08.239 --> 00:21:15.199
So the idea here is, if I've trained a model on a million observations, I get 100,000 more.

00:21:16.079 --> 00:21:22.640
Do I have to go back and run the algorithm on all of those million and 100,000 observations,

00:21:22.640 --> 00:21:27.920
or is there some way to incorporate the information from those 100,000 into the original?

00:21:28.079 --> 00:21:33.680
Only a subset of engines in tidy models will be able to do that.

00:21:33.680 --> 00:21:39.520
That just depends on what the model supports.

00:21:40.400 --> 00:21:44.319
But if that's available through the modeling engine, then you can interface with it in

00:21:44.319 --> 00:21:45.359
tidy models as well.

00:21:49.040 --> 00:21:49.599
Awesome.

00:21:49.599 --> 00:21:50.160
Thank you.

