00:26:24.400 --> 00:26:25.920
And what are you most excited about?

00:26:28.479 --> 00:26:36.239
We have two sort of big efforts that the team has been focusing on throughout this year.

00:26:36.239 --> 00:26:41.680
And both of them are very close to being released, which I'm super excited about.

00:26:42.800 --> 00:26:46.719
One of them is better tooling for survival analysis.

00:26:47.680 --> 00:26:58.959
So the censored package in tidy models has a lot of the bread and butter code for how

00:26:58.959 --> 00:26:59.839
all that will happen.

00:27:00.479 --> 00:27:04.719
And we're working on integrating that with the rest of the ecosystem.

00:27:05.680 --> 00:27:10.479
And so I think in the coming months, hopefully by the new year, we'll have lots of

00:27:11.119 --> 00:27:14.800
documentation and some release notes about how that came together.

00:27:15.760 --> 00:27:21.199
The other thing that I've personally been spending a lot of time on, and this is coming

00:27:21.199 --> 00:27:27.920
about after we brought together a reading group within Posit about model fairness.

00:27:28.719 --> 00:27:36.959
So if a model is predicting outcomes that are somehow related to people, we want to

00:27:36.959 --> 00:27:44.079
make sure that we understand the ways that a model might predict values differently.

00:27:44.880 --> 00:27:46.719
For different subpopulations.

00:27:48.479 --> 00:27:55.280
And there's all sorts of tooling out there for learning about how models understand

00:27:55.280 --> 00:27:58.880
information about subpopulations.

00:27:59.439 --> 00:28:05.599
And we've been putting together some functionality so that people can interface with those

00:28:05.599 --> 00:28:07.040
methods using tidy model.

